	                        <div id="dsq-comment-message-3063308484" class="dsq-comment-message">
	                            <div id="dsq-comment-text-3063308484" class="dsq-comment-text">
	                                <p>Hey Shairyar!</p><p>I'm not completely sure, but I believe the issue is that Postgres (being a pretty smart database) has a special JSON field type - see details here: <a href="http://disq.us/url?url=http%3A%2F%2Fstackoverflow.com%2Fquestions%2F29539370%2Fdoctrine-query-postgres-json-contains-json-array%3A-NgnakFdHaWFmZRRb7ZSBYddYuE&amp;cuid=1175718" rel="nofollow noopener">http://stackoverflow.com/quest...</a>. So, with MySQL, this is just saved in a string field where the contents are JSON (and the LIKE query works). But Postgresql I believe puts it into an actual, native JSON field. This is actually good, as I believe they more natively support searching on the contents of that field, but I'm not exactly sure how that query would look. The StackOverflow has a few links that might contain some things to try out.</p><p>Let us know if this helps point you in the right direction!</p><p>Cheers!</p>
	                            </div>
